Low 77F. Winds SE at 5 to 10 mph. Chance of rain 40%.. Clear skies this evening will give way to occasional showers overnight. Low 77F. Winds SE at 5 to 10 mph. Chance of rain 40%. Updated: June 16, 2024 @ 4:55 pm Paul Bruce Paul Bruce said he is excited to announce his candidacy for Walker County Sheriff. As Sheriff, he plans to be an active and engaged Sheriff who brings advanced leadership to build a safer community — both of which he believes Walker County residents deserve. He recently commented on other principles which he believes in and knows Walker County citizens deserve, saying, “Whether we want it to or not, Walker County is about to experience significant population growth. I will do everything in my power to assist in preparing for the growth by improving our sheriff’s office service and growing the department.” He continued, “We grow the office by developing community partnerships, developing problem-oriented policing, investing in technology, and improving communication with the community.” He comes from a distinguished family of public service with his father, brothers, cousins, and uncles having served as Texas peace officers throughout the state. He first came to Huntsville in 1992 to attend college at Sam Houston State University. However, life experiences happened and his father, a Houston Police Officer was run over by a car thief as he was attempting to apprehend the suspect. He suffered a massive stroke and was medically retired after 25 years of service. Bruce went home and helped his mother and brothers care for his father. He later joined the United States Army in 1996 and served four years. While in the Army, he deployed to Bosnia, Austria for a Humanitarian mission and Kuwait in between the two Gulf Wars. This is where he developed his leadership style. Bruce leads from the front and takes care of his troops. He is currently serving as a Captain at the largest Sheriff’s Office in the State of Texas and the third in the nation. As a Division Commander, he has experience in all areas of the Sheriff’s Office from Patrol, Jails, Background, Recruiting, Human Resources, Criminal Investigations, and Emergency Dispatch. He has served in law enforcement for 25 years (Montgomery County and Harris County Sheriff’s Office). Bruce believes in transparency and informing the community of what is going on. He said last week, “The current administration lacks transparency. Information is not shared with the community; it is stale when it becomes available.” Bruce has a history of communication with the public, media, and other law enforcement agencies. He went a step further, making a commitment, “I will create a Sheriff’s Office Facebook page as well as create a Walker County Sheriff’s Office interactive Website to keep the public informed. Other area sheriff’s offices have used social media and websites to huge advantages for their deputies and for citizens of their counties.” His educational background has prepared him for this endeavor. He has an Associate’s degree in Criminal Justice from North Harris Community College, a Bachelor’s degree in Criminal Justice from the University of Houston Downtown, and a Master’s Degree in Leadership and Management from Sam Houston State University. He also graduated from the Bill Blackwood Leadership Command College class #90. As a leader he encourages those who work with him to continue their higher education and training. He has been heard saying many times, “Education is invaluable, and I encourage everyone to increase their knowledge and skills.” Bruce listens to the community’s needs and thinks outside the box to come up with inventive solutions. His goals are to increase patrol through state and federal grants, and deputy reserve programs (volunteers) by bringing federal and state taxpayers’ money back to Walker County. He says he will invest in new technology to help solve crimes and maximize effectiveness and efficiency, as well as provide advanced training to his staff and encourage community involvement. He believes the staff is the most important asset a department has for its citizens. Bruce said he brings integrity and will be a Sheriff for all citizens. His beliefs are “Integrity is doing the right thing, even when no one is watching,” (C.S. Lewis). He said he treats everyone with respect, looks forward to improving the Sheriff’s Office, and working for the great citizens of Walker County when elected as Sheriff. Bruce met his wife, Morgan, at a country western dance hall by asking her to dance. Bruce said they fell in love instantly and have been together for 11 years. They have two daughters, Paisley and Rylan. Paul and Morgan moved to Walker County four and a half years ago to raise their family. Bruce said he is a proud father of two daughters who barrel race, and also attend Huntsville ISD. For more information, those interested should visit the campaign Facebook page, website at paulbruceforsheriff.com, or email Paul at PaulBruceForSheriff@gmail.com.
